label a4_s17_selene_route_slow:

    a "I want this."

    a "I want this and I want it slowly. I have been walking toward this room for three days and I do not want to sprint the last meter. I want to sit with you on the edge of the bed and I want to undo the clip at the back of your neck and I want to learn the shape of your hair when you have not put it into a braid for command. I want to start at the neck and I want to let the scene take the time the scene wants. I do not want to arrive somewhere by midnight because midnight is a clock and the clock is not in this room."

    a "That is the honest sentence."

    "Her eyes have not left his face."

    sel "My sentence is: I want you in a room with no clock. I have not been in a room with no clock since I was thirty-one. The clock is my vocation. Tonight I am going to put the clock in the drawer with the letter."

    sel "Slowly. Yes."

    "She moves her hand from his jaw to the back of her own neck. She finds the clip. She does not undo it."

    sel "Undo it for me."

    "He lifts his hands. The clip is small and his fingers are not good at small things tonight. He undoes it on the second try. Her hair comes down — not all the way, the memory of the braid still in it — and his hand catches the weight of it at the nape."

    "She closes her eyes at the touch."

    sel "The bed."

    "She takes his other hand. She walks him the four paces."

    "She turns the desk lamp off. The letter goes into the dark."

    "She sits on the edge of the bed. She does not pull him down with her. She looks up."

    sel "I want you to start at my wrist."

    a "Your wrist."

    sel "The hand I put on your jaw. Start there. Work inward. You are going to find where the hand came from. I am going to find where it is now. Slowly."

    "He sits beside her."

    # [INTIMATE CONTENT HERE]
    # (User writes this beat. Selene erotic deepening — slow
    # variant. The pacing is the subject. He starts at her wrist.
    # The pacing is the grammar of a woman who has been moving at
    # the speed of war for three years and is being allowed, for
    # the first time in that duration, to move at the speed of her
    # own body. The bed lamp is the only light. The letter is on
    # the desk, face-down, in darkness. Do not cut to aftercare
    # until the body of the scene is complete on its own terms.)

    jump a4_s17_selene_aftercare_intimate

label a4_s17_selene_route_sit:

    a "I don't know if I want what I came here wanting."

    a "I came here to tell you I see you. I said it. I am standing in the room where I said it. I am holding you and you are holding me and we have been inside the sentence for twelve minutes now. And what I want — what I actually want, Selene, the honest sentence — is to sit on the floor with you and read your sister's letter together."

    a "Not because I want the information. Not because I want to build a retrieval plan. Because I want to sit on the floor with you and let you say the words of it out loud to another person in this room, and let you not carry Ilene alone for an hour."

    a "The bed can be tomorrow. Or next week. Or never, if never is the shape the scene wants. Tonight I want to sit with you and I want the letter to be on the floor between us and I want to hear your sister's sentences in your voice."

    a "That is the honest sentence."

    "A long beat."

    "Her face does the small-move from three nights ago. Then her face does something else — something the s12a scene did not have room for. The corner of her mouth holds for a beat and then she lets her whole mouth go soft, and it is not a smile, it is the shape a face makes when it has been holding a single expression for a long time and is allowed to stop."

    sel "You came here for me and you are offering to spend the hour on my sister."

    a "They are the same person."

    sel "No they are not."

    a "No. You are right. They are not. I am offering anyway."

    "A beat. Her hand is still on his face."

    sel "My sentence was going to be: I want you to stay until morning. That was my sentence. I was going to ask you to stay until morning and I was going to mean it as the whole sentence and I did not know which version of staying you were going to mean it as."

    sel "You just gave me a version I had not considered."

    sel "I am going to accept that version."

    "She takes his hand."

    "She does not walk him to the bed."

    "She walks him to the desk."

    "She picks up the letter — face-up this time, hers — and she carries it to the floor between the desk and the bed. She sits down. Back against the side of the bed frame, knees up. She pats the floor beside her — not opposite her this time, beside her, shoulder-to-shoulder."

    "He sits."

    "Their shoulders are touching. Their knees are up. The letter is in her hands, between them, on her lap."

    "She unfolds it along the soft crease."

    sel "Ilene's handwriting is a little slanted. She was left-handed and the Academy tried to fix her at eight years old and she refused and they left her alone because she was our grandmother's favorite. I am going to read it to you from the beginning. You are going to interrupt me when you want to. That is the rule of this version."

    a "Understood."

    "She begins to read."

    sel "'Dear Sel. The cat came again this morning.'"

    "She pauses. He does not interrupt. He has decided not to interrupt for the first paragraph, to let her find the shape of reading aloud, because she has not read this letter aloud yet and her voice has not met her sister's handwriting in open air."

    sel "'It was at the door before I was. I think it sleeps somewhere along the wall of the building next door, because the step is still warm when I open the door in the morning — the cat has been sitting there. It is not afraid of me anymore. Two months ago it would have bolted. Now it lets me put a saucer down and it waits for me to step back before it eats, because that is the arrangement. I step back. It eats. We respect each other's geometry.'"

    "A beat. She looks at him."

    sel "She wrote geometry."

    a "Yes."

    sel "Our mother used to say that. About corridors in the Academy. About where to stand when you did not want to be pulled into a conversation. 'Respect the geometry of the room.' Ilene is using her at me across six weeks of courier chain."

    a "Your sister knows your grammar."

    sel "My sister is my grammar."

    "She looks down at the letter. She resumes."

    sel "'She let me touch the back of her neck yesterday for the first time. I have been wanting to tell you that for three weeks and the courier was not running. I touched her on the spot between the shoulders where her spine makes a small ridge, and she held still, and I did not push further, because the arrangement is: back of the neck only. Not the belly. Not the head. I think maybe in a month I can try the head.'"

    "A beat."

    sel "She says 'maybe in a month.' She does not know if she has a month."

    a "No."

    sel "I do not know if she has a month either."

    a "No."

    sel "I am going to read it anyway."

    a "Yes. Read it."

    "She reads the rest of the letter."

    "He does not interrupt. At two places she pauses and he puts his hand flat on the floor near her thigh — not touching her, near her — and the hand is the sentence that means keep going, and she reads the next line. At the third pause he says one word, which is the word 'ok,' and she says thank you and reads the next line. At the end of the letter she folds it again along the soft crease and she puts it on the floor between her thigh and his, and she rests her head on his shoulder, and she exhales the longest breath she has exhaled in a week and a half."

    "They sit like that for a long time."

    "Eventually her head gets heavier against his shoulder and he realizes, in the slow incremental way a person realizes these things, that she is not asleep yet but she is about to be, and he is the thing keeping her upright, and he is going to stay the thing keeping her upright for however long she sleeps like this, and when she wakes up she is going to have slept for the first time in seventy-two hours, and she is going to look at him and she is going to decide what tomorrow's version of the room looks like, and he is going to meet her where she is."

    "He does not move."

    "Fade slow."

    jump a4_s17_selene_aftercare_nonintimate

label a4_s17_selene_aftercare_intimate:

    # ========== PHASE 8a — AFTERCARE (INTIMATE VARIANT) ==========

    # CAMERA: pull back from the macro vocabulary. 35mm
    #         two-shot, loose. They are in her bed now,
    #         or against it, or near it — whichever the
    #         narrative has placed them. The second
    #         practical lamp is closer to them now. The
    #         letter is still on the desk, face-down,
    #         at the edge of the frame. Hold the wide.
    #         No music enters until after this phase
    #         begins — and when it does, it is the
    #         lowest register string the Act 4 score
    #         has used yet. Barely audible. Holding.

    # CAMERA: 50mm. Hold on Selene's face against the pillow, Aeron's
    # shoulder at the edge of frame. Not a two-shot for the first beat —
    # her face alone. The pillow is hers. She has been sleeping on it
    # alone for three years.
    # LIGHTING: Bed lamp only. The desk is in the dark. The letter is
    # in the dark. The room has shrunk to the width of the bed.
    # SFX: Her breath. His breath. The ambient hum. No music.

    "The bed lamp is still on."

    "Her head is on the pillow, her body turned toward him, the sheet pulled up to her ribs. His hand is at the small of her back — the same place it was during the forehead beat, because his hand has found a grammar and it is not letting go of it."

    "Her eyes are open. Not wide. Soft. She has not spoken for a while. Neither has he."

    "The first sentence of the aftercare is not the one he is expecting."

    sel "I have been trying to be Kael."

    "A beat."

    sel "I did not notice until you saw me."

    "He does not interrupt."

    sthought "The sentence is out of my mouth and I cannot put it back. I am not going to try to put it back. The sentence has been inside my teeth for eighteen years and I am going to let it be in the room."

    sel "I have been teaching you the way Kael used to teach me. Not because I miss him and not because I am trying to bring him back and not because you look like him — you do not look like him, you do not walk like him, you are a very different shape of man than Kael was, and that has been the entire reason this has worked. I have been teaching you the way Kael taught me because Kael taught me by making me competent and I have been making you competent because competence was the only curriculum he had for a twenty-two-year-old girl who had just lost her parents, and it was the only curriculum I had for you, because it is the only curriculum I know how to transmit."

    sel "Competence is grief-shaped."

    sel "Kael was grieving his wife. The wife I never met. The wife he never said her name out loud, he only looked at a particular corner of the war room and the corner was her. He taught me competence because competence was the grammar of surviving her absence without falling apart. I was his student and I was also the thing he was using to not fall apart."

    sel "I did not know that for a long time. I figured it out at thirty-one, the year I finally cried in front of another person for the first time, and the other person was Kael, and I cried about a mission we had lost and he cried about his wife and we did not say either of those things out loud. We just cried at the same table with a map between us."

    sel "I have been doing the same thing to you."

    sel "I have been teaching you competence because competence is the grammar of surviving Ilene's absence. I have been making you good at command because if I make you good at command, someone is going to walk out of the war room tomorrow and lead, and the person leading will be you, and the person leading being you means I was useful today, and being useful is how I have been surviving the fact that I cannot retrieve my sister."

    sel "You have been the retrieval operation I was allowed to do."

    sel "I have been displacing grief into doctrine and you have been receiving the doctrine and the doctrine has been working and all of this is true and none of this is your fault and I am telling you because tonight you said I am not here to be your student and you meant it, and the sentence cost something I have been unwilling to pay for eighteen years."

    "A beat."

    sel "I do not know who I am if I am not the teacher. I am going to have to find out."

    sel "I am going to have to find out in the same room where I have been teaching. Which is — it is a room shaped like my life. The room does not have a not-teacher version of me in it yet. The room is going to have to grow one."

    sel "You can be in the room while I find her."

    sel "You have been in the room for three years. This is not a new request. It is the same request I have been making without the word for it, and tonight I have the word."

    sel "The word is: stay."

    "A very long beat."

    "He moves his hand from the small of her back to the side of her face — the same angle her hand was on his jaw earlier, a symmetry his body has registered without his mind being told about it."

    a "I am going to be in the room."

    a "I am going to be here for whoever you find when you find her. I am not going to demand a timetable. I am not going to ask you to report progress. I am going to stay in the room the way I stood in the corridor three nights ago — listening for the pitch of the door, coming back when the pitch is the pitch of a compromise, standing at the chair when the chair is the offering."

    a "You have been teaching me out of grief. I know."

    a "And what you taught me is still the teaching. It is still real. It is still the reason I am going to be able to lead the thing Marcus is building toward. The teaching does not become false because the teacher was grieving. The teaching becomes — large. Larger than I was. I can hold that now. I could not have held it two weeks ago."

    a "I can hold it tonight."

    a "I can hold you tonight."

    "A beat."

    a "I see you."

    "She closes her eyes."

    "She does not answer in words. She turns her face into his palm and she breathes once against it, and the breath is the acknowledgment, and it is the last thing either of them says before the sleep she has not had in seventy-two hours finally arrives and takes her."

    "He watches her fall asleep."

    "He does not move his hand from her face until her breath is deep and even. Then he moves it, slowly, to the space between them on the sheet, and his fingers find her fingers, and he closes his hand over hers."

    "The bed lamp stays on for a while longer."

    "He will turn it off eventually. Not yet."

    "Fade."

    jump a4_s17_selene_scene_close

label a4_s17_selene_aftercare_nonintimate:

    # ========== PHASE 8b — AFTERCARE (NON-INTIMATE VARIANT) ==========

    "They are still on the floor, shoulder against bed frame, her head on his shoulder."

    "The letter is folded on the floor beside her thigh."

    "She has been half-asleep for about twelve minutes and now she is awake again, the way a very tired person wakes in stages, and the first stage is the one where the body decides it is not done saying something."

    sthought "He offered the letter instead of the bed."

    sthought "I did not know a person could do that. I did not know the offer was available. I have been in rooms with men who offered one or the other and I have been in rooms with men who offered one and meant the other. I have never been in a room with a man who offered the bed, heard my grief inside his own want, revised the offer in real time, and kept wanting me in the revision."

    sthought "He wants me. I am not going to mistake what just happened for an absence of wanting. He wants me. He also wants Ilene out of my throat for an hour. The wanting and the other wanting are not separate wantings. They are the same wanting, and the word for the shape of them together is a word I have not had until tonight."

    sthought "The word is: care."

    sthought "I have been cared about. I have not been cared for like this. Care as a verb, with an object, where the object is me."

    "She lifts her head from his shoulder."

    "She turns so she can see his face."

    sel "I have been trying to be Kael."

    "A beat."

    sel "I did not notice until you saw me."

    "He does not interrupt."

    sel "Kael taught me competence because competence was the grammar of surviving his wife's absence. I have been teaching you competence because competence is the grammar of surviving Ilene's absence. I have been making you good at command because making you good at command has been the retrieval operation I have been allowed to do."

    sel "You have been the retrieval."

    sel "I did not know that until tonight. I have been teaching a doctrine and calling it doctrine and the doctrine has been real and has been useful and has been landing in you the way it was supposed to land, and the thing underneath the doctrine has been a woman carrying a sister in a sector she cannot reach, pouring the carrying into the nearest living person who would take it."

    sel "Tonight you came here and you told me you were not coming to be taught. You told me you were coming to see me. And I could not receive that at first because being seen is not a thing I have practiced receiving — I have practiced being competent at being seen, which is not the same as being seen — and then you offered the letter and the floor and I —"

    sel "I am competent at grief, Aeron. I am competent at teaching. I am competent at running the war room. I am not competent at being held."

    sel "I am going to have to learn. I am going to have to learn in the room where I have been teaching. Which is a room shaped like my life, and the room does not have a version of me that knows how to be held inside it yet, and the room is going to have to grow one."

    sel "You can be in the room while I grow her."

    sel "That is the request."

    "A long beat. He has not moved."

    a "I am going to be in the room."

    a "I am not going to demand a timetable. I am not going to ask you to report progress. I am going to stay in the room the way I stood in the corridor three nights ago. Listening. Coming back when the pitch is the pitch of a compromise."

    a "You have been teaching me out of grief. I know that now. And the teaching is still the teaching. It is still real. It is still the reason I am going to be able to lead whatever Marcus is building toward. The teaching does not become false because the teacher was grieving."

    a "The teaching becomes large. Larger than I was. I can hold that now."

    a "I can hold you tonight."

    "A beat."

    a "I see you."

    "She closes her eyes."

    "She puts her head back on his shoulder."

    "She does not answer in words. She exhales once against the side of his neck, and the exhale is the acknowledgment, and it is the last thing either of them says for a while."

    "They stay on the floor for another forty minutes."

    "At some point she falls asleep against him. He does not move. When his shoulder starts to cramp he shifts his weight a fraction, slowly, and she does not wake. He will stay on this floor until the oh-six-hundred brief is two hours away, and then he will wake her gently, and she will look at him with the face of a woman who has slept against a shoulder for the first time in eighteen years, and she will decide what the morning version of the room looks like, and he will meet her where she is."

    "None of that has happened yet."

    "Right now the letter is on the floor beside her thigh and her head is on his shoulder and the desk lamp is still on and the clock is in the drawer with the letter's absence, and the room is holding two people and one cat named Grandmother and a sister who may or may not still be feeding the cat, and Aeron is in the room for all of them."

    "Fade slow."

    jump a4_s17_selene_scene_close

label a4_s17_selene_scene_close:

    # stop ambient fadeout 4.0
    # scene black with fade

    # ========= STATE UPDATES =========
    $ rel_bump("Selene", trust=2, attraction=2)
    $ canon_set("selene.seen_as_person", True)
    $ canon_set("selene.admitted_competence_is_grief_shaped", True)
    $ canon_set("selene.kael_displacement_spoken_aloud", True)
    $ flag("selene_cried_in_front_of_aeron", True)
    $ flag("selene_erotic_deepening_emp", True)
    $ npc_remember("Selene", "let_him_arrive_as_something_else", tone="received")
    $ npc_remember("Selene", "named_kael_displacement_aloud", tone="unguarded")
    $ npc_remember("Aeron", "came_not_to_be_taught", tone="witnessing")
    $ npc_remember("Aeron", "offered_the_letter_instead_of_the_bed", tone="revised_want")
    $ tp_seed("a4.selene.held_as_woman")
    $ tp_seed("a4.selene.grief_doctrine_named")
    $ metric("selene_unguarded_moments_witnessed", delta=2)
    $ nudge_poly("selene", "care_as_verb", delta=1)
    $ scene_mark(_current_scene_id, "exited")

    return


